  "text": "The Rust standard library implements the async runtime waker mechanism across multiple files in the core and alloc libraries. The central file is library/core/src/task/wake.rs, which defines the RawWaker struct (lines 22-31) as a low-level abstraction containing a data pointer and a vtable pointer. The RawWakerVTable struct (lines 108-140) defines the virtual function table with four function pointers: clone, wake, wake_by_ref, and drop. These functions follow unsafe semantics as they operate on raw pointers. The Waker struct (lines 407-409) wraps the RawWaker in a thread-safe, ergonomic interface that implements Send and Sync traits. LocalWaker (lines 740-742) provides a non-thread-safe alternative using Rc instead of Arc. Context (lines 218-230) and ContextBuilder (lines 301-313) provide the execution context passed to futures during polling, holding references to Waker and LocalWaker instances. The Future trait in library/core/src/future/future.rs defines the core polling interface with the poll method (line 113) that takes a Context and returns a Poll result. The Poll enum in library/core/src/task/poll.rs provides Ready(T) and Pending variants that represent the future's completion status. The Wake trait in library/alloc/src/task.rs enables safe, ergonomic waker construction from Arc-wrapped types. Functions raw_waker (lines 137-177) and local_raw_waker (lines 315-350) construct RawWaker instances from Wake and LocalWake trait implementations, managing reference counting through the vtable functions. The polling loop mechanism is not explicitly implemented in the standard library but follows the pattern: futures are polled within a Context, storing the Waker when returning Pending; external events trigger Waker::wake or Waker::wake_by_ref to reschedule the task; executor re-polls the future when woken. This design enables efficient, callback-free async runtimes like tokio and async-std to build on core primitives."
}

